╭────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
│ ✓  WriteFile Writing to petrosa-cio/.../overview.md                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                │
│   1 # System Architecture & Orchestration                                                                                                      │
│   2                                                                                                                                            │
│   3 **Source:** `../investigations/004-llm-prompt-guide-reference.md` (Version 1.0)                                                            │
│   4                                                                                                                                            │
│   5 ## 1. System Overview                                                                                                                      │
│   6                                                                                                                                            │
│   7 PETROSA is an autonomous quantitative trading intelligence system running on Kubernetes. It manages 34 live trading strategies (28 in      │
│     TA-bot, 6 in realtime-strategies) and makes parameter adjustment and trade execution decisions without human intervention.                 │
│   8                                                                                                                                            │
│   9 The CIO (Chief Intelligence Officer) is the autonomous brain. It receives trade intents from strategies via NATS, intercepts them, and     │
│     decides: execute, modify, skip, or block. It also monitors strategy health and proactively adjusts parameters when market conditions       │
│     change.                                                                                                                                    │
│  10                                                                                                                                            │
│  11 ### High-Level Data Flow                                                                                                                   │
│  12                                                                                                                                            │
│  13 ```                                                                                                                                        │
│  14 strategies → NATS intent.* → CIO → TradeEngine                                                                                             │
│  15                               ↕                                                                                                            │
│  16                       Strategy APIs (TA-bot, Realtime)                                                                                     │
│  17                               ↕                                                                                                            │
│  18                       petrosa-data-manager                                                                                                 │
│  19 ```                                                                                                                                        │
│  20                                                                                                                                            │
│  21 **Core Responsibilities:**                                                                                                                 │
│  22 - **Intercept:** Capture trade signals before execution.                                                                                   │
│  23 - **Enforce:** Apply hard risk limits (drawdown, order counts).                                                                            │
│  24 - **Decide:** Evaluate market regime and strategy health to determine action.                                                              │
│  25 - **Act:** Execute trades, modify strategy parameters, or block unsafe actions.                                                            │
│  26                                                                                                                                            │
│  27 ## 2. Design Principles                                                                                                                    │
│  28                                                                                                                                            │
│  29 Four principles govern every design decision in this framework.                                                                            │
│  30                                                                                                                                            │
│  31 **Principle 1 — Code owns numbers, LLMs own language.**                                                                                    │
│  32 Any output that is a number computed from other numbers is produced by a Python function. LLMs are called only when the input is natural   │
│     language context (regime descriptions, strategy documentation, qualitative health signals) and the output is a classification. LLMs        │
│     hallucinate floats. This is not a limitation to work around — it is a constraint to design for.                                            │
│  33                                                                                                                                            │
│  34 **Principle 2 — Maximum three LLM calls per decision.**                                                                                    │
│  35 The entire decision pipeline runs on at most three LLM calls: Regime Classifier, Strategy Assessor, Action Classifier. Everything else is  │
│     code. On the HOT path, this drops to zero LLM calls when cached assessments are valid.                                                     │
│  36                                                                                                                                            │
│  37 **Principle 3 — Schemas must have four fields or fewer.**                                                                                  │
│  38 Every LLM output schema has at most four top-level fields. Above this limit, small models begin omitting fields, inventing field names, or │
│     producing malformed JSON. Smaller schemas mean fewer parse failures and cheaper outputs.                                                   │
│  39                                                                                                                                            │
│  40 **Principle 4 — Determinism through hard gates, not LLM judgment.**                                                                        │
│  41 All hard limits (drawdown, order counts, minimum EV) are enforced by code before any LLM is called. LLMs are never in a position to        │
│     "decide" whether to override a safety limit. The code blocks the action before the LLM sees the request.                                   │
│  42                                                                                                                                            │
│  43 ## 3. Code vs LLM Decision Matrix                                                                                                          │
│  44                                                                                                                                            │
│  45 Before any prompt is written, every decision must be classified. This table is the authoritative reference:                                │
│  46                                                                                                                                            │
│  47 | Decision | Owner | Reason |                                                                                                              │
│  48 |---|---|---|                                                                                                                              │
│  49 | Hard limit checks (drawdown, max orders) | **Code** | Binary, deterministic, safety-critical |                                           │
│  50 | Expected value calculation | **Code** | Arithmetic — LLMs hallucinate floats |                                                           │
│  51 | Kelly fraction | **Code** | Formula with no ambiguity |                                                                                  │
│  52 | Fee + slippage + funding cost | **Code** | Arithmetic |                                                                                  │
│  53 | Position size | **Code** | Derived from Kelly × scale factors |                                                                          │
│  54 | Stop loss / take profit levels | **Code** | Strategy default × lookup multiplier |                                                       │
│  55 | Capital utilisation ratio | **Code** | Division |                                                                                        │
│  56 | Portfolio concentration check | **Code** | Sum and comparison |                                                                          │
│  57 | Trigger routing (HOT/WARM/COLD) | **Code** | Switch statement on trigger_type enum |                                                     │
│  58 | Order type selection | **Code** | Rule: spread_pct < threshold → limit |                                                                 │
│  59 | Parameter value computation | **Code** | Direction signal × step size × schema bounds |                                                  │
│  60 | Hard exit triggers | **Code** | Stop loss / take profit / time expiry comparisons |                                                      │
│  61 | Market regime classification | **LLM** | Multi-signal pattern recognition |                                                              │
│  62 | Strategy qualitative fit assessment | **LLM** | Natural language strategy docs + regime context |                                        │
│  63 | Action classification | **LLM** | Synthesising flags + qualitative assessments |                                                         │
│  64 | Parameter change justification | **LLM** | Audit trace grounded in strategy docs |                                                       │
│  65                                                                                                                                            │
│  66 The split is roughly 75% code, 25% LLM. Code handles all quantitative work. LLMs handle classification and language.                       │
│  67                                                                                                                                            │
│  68 ## 4. Orchestration Pipeline                                                                                                               │
│  69                                                                                                                                            │
│  70 ```                                                                                                                                        │
│  71 TRIGGER RECEIVED (NATS intent.* or scheduled)                                                                                              │
│  72               │                                                                                                                            │
│  73               ▼                                                                                                                            │
│  74 ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐                                                                                │
│  75 │                   TRIGGER GATE (code)                   │                                                                                │
│  76 │                                                         │                                                                                │
│  77 │  1. Parse trigger_type and payload                      │                                                                                │
│  78 │  2. Run hard limit checks against RiskLimits config     │                                                                                │
│  79 │  3. If any hard limit breached → BLOCK, exit immediately│                                                                                │
│  80 │  4. Check TTL — if expired → discard, log, exit         │                                                                                │
│  81 │  5. Route to HOT / WARM / COLD path                     │                                                                                │
│  82 └────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┘                                                                                │
│  83                          │                                                                                                                 │
